Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Abd Al-Muttalib Ibreighith¶

Introduction¶

The dataset consists of 183,412 bike trip records collected from a bike-sharing program. It includes 16 features related to trip details, user information, and station locations. Below is a summary table of the dataset's columns:

Column Description
duration_sec Duration of the trip in seconds
start_time Timestamp for the start of the trip
end_time Timestamp for the end of the trip
start_station_id ID of the starting station
start_station_name Name of the starting station
start_station_latitude Latitude of the starting station
start_station_longitude Longitude of the starting station
end_station_id ID of the ending station
end_station_name Name of the ending station
end_station_latitude Latitude of the ending station
end_station_longitude Longitude of the ending station
bike_id ID of the bike used in the trip
user_type Type of user (Customer or Subscriber)
member_birth_year Birth year of the member
member_gender Gender of the member
bike_share_for_all_trip Whether the bike was shared for the entire trip (Yes/No)

This dataset allows for a detailed analysis of bike usage patterns, user demographics, and station-specific details.

Correct datatypes¶

Let's correct the data types of several columns in the DataFrame df. It converts start_time and end_time to datetime types, start_station_id, end_station_id, and member_birth_year to int64, and maps the bike_share_for_all_trip column from 'No' and 'Yes' to boolean values. So, we ensure consistency and reliable data.

In [69]:
# Correct start_time and end_time datatypes into datetime type
df_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean['start_time'])
df_clean['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean['end_time'])

# Correct ids datatypes into int64
df_clean['start_station_id'] = df_clean['start_station_id'].astype('int64')
df_clean['end_station_id'] = df_clean['end_station_id'].astype('int64')

# Correct member_birth_year datatype into int64
df_clean['member_birth_year'] = df_clean['member_birth_year'].astype('int64')

# Correct bike_share_for_all_trip(No=False/Yes=True) datatype into boolean
df_clean['bike_share_for_all_trip'] = df_clean['bike_share_for_all_trip'].map({'No': False, 'Yes': True})

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

There are 174,952 bike trips in the dataset with 16 features. Most variables are numeric in nature, such as duration_sec, start_station_id, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, and member_birth_year. However, several variables are categorical or textual, including start_time, end_time (representing timestamps), start_station_name, end_station_name (station names), user_type (customer or subscriber), member_gender (gender of the member), and bike_share_for_all_trip (indicating whether the bike was shared for the entire trip).

What are the main features of interest in the dataset?¶

The main features of interest appear to be:

  • duration_sec: This feature indicates the duration of each bike trip, which can provide insights into ride lengths and usage patterns.
  • start_time and end_time: These features provide timestamps for the start and end of each trip, enabling analysis of temporal trends and peak usage times.
  • start_station_name and end_station_name: These categorical features identify the starting and ending locations of each trip, useful for understanding popular routes and station utilization.
  • user_type: This categorical feature distinguishes between customers and subscribers, offering insights into user demographics and behavior patterns.

These features collectively provide a comprehensive view of bike trip durations, temporal patterns, station usage, and user characteristics within your dataset.

What features in the dataset will help to support the investigation of the features of interest?¶

To investigate the features of interest in the dataset, several other features will support the analysis:

  1. Geospatial Features: start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude can help visualize and analyze the geographic distribution of bike trips and station locations.

  2. Demographic Features: member_birth_year and member_gender will aid in understanding the demographics of riders and how they correlate with trip characteristics.

  3. Temporal Features: Besides start_time and end_time, additional temporal features such as day of the week, month, or season derived from timestamps can help uncover patterns in bike usage over time.

  4. Trip Specifics: bike_id can track individual bikes and their usage patterns, while bike_share_for_all_trip indicates whether the bike was shared for the entire trip, potentially influencing trip duration and usage.

  5. Station Details: Further details about stations such as start_station_id and end_station_id could provide additional context about station infrastructure or characteristics affecting trip patterns.

These features collectively provide context and additional dimensions to analyze and interpret the main features of interest in your dataset related to bike trip durations, user behaviors, and station usage patterns.

In this section, we investigate the distributions of individual variables. This helps in identifying unusual points or outliers and prepares us to explore relationships between variables.

Question 1: What are the trip durations?¶

Visualization:¶

In [72]:
# Plot the histogram for trip durations
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 4))
binsize = 300
bins = np.arange(0, df_clean['duration_sec'].max() + binsize, binsize)

sns.histplot(df_clean['duration_sec'], bins=bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Duration (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

# Plot the histogram for trip durations excluding outliers
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 4))
binsize = 100
bins = np.arange(0, df_clean['duration_sec'].quantile(0.99) + binsize, binsize)

sns.histplot(df_clean['duration_sec'], bins=bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations\n(Top 1% of duration values excluded)')
plt.xlabel('Duration (seconds)')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • Distribution Shape: The distribution of trip durations is right-skewed. Most trips are relatively short, with the majority of durations falling between 100 and 1000 seconds.

  • Central Tendency: There is a peak around 500 seconds, suggesting that a significant number of trips tend to be around this duration.

  • Long Tail: There are fewer trips with very long durations, extending up to 100,000 seconds. This long tail indicates that while most trips are short, there are a few exceptionally long trips.

  • Outliers: The presence of very long trip durations may suggest outliers or unusual trips that could require further investigation.

These observations provide a clear understanding of the trip duration distribution and highlight areas that may need further analysis, such as the reasons behind the long-duration trips.

In [73]:
def countplotter(x, data, hue, title, xlabel, ylabel): 
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    sns.countplot(x=x, data=data, hue=hue, palette='viridis')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Trip Durations¶

The histogram of trip durations shows a right-skewed distribution. Most trips are relatively short, clustered around the lower end of the duration scale, with the frequency peaking at around 500 seconds. The distribution then tapers off as the duration increases, indicating fewer long trips. The log scale on the x-axis helps to better visualize the spread of trip durations, especially for the longer trips which are less frequent. There were no unusual points observed that required transformations for this variable.

Member Birth Years¶

The histogram of member birth years exhibits a left-skewed distribution, with most members born between the 1960s and 2000. The highest frequency is observed for members born around the late 1980s and early 1990s. A few outliers exist for birth years earlier than 1940, which might need further inspection to ensure data accuracy.

Bike Share for All Trip¶

The bar chart for bike sharing indicates that the majority of riders did not share their bikes for all trips. There is a significant disparity between those who shared and those who did not, with non-sharers vastly outnumbering sharers. No transformations were necessary for this variable.

User Types¶

The bar chart for user types shows that the dataset contains two types of users: customers and subscribers. Subscribers are more frequent than customers. This straightforward distribution did not require any transformations.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Of the features investigated, the member birth year distribution had some unusual points (outliers for birth years before 1940). These points could be due to data entry errors or older members who are outliers in the age distribution. No significant transformations were performed on these distributions, but it might be useful to clean the data by investigating and potentially removing these outliers to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the analysis.

For the trip duration distribution, the use of a logarithmic scale was essential due to the wide range of values. This adjustment was necessary to make the distribution more interpretable, especially given the long tail for longer trip durations.

No transformations were necessary for the bike sharing, and user type distributions.

Question 5: How does the average duration of bike trips vary across different days of the week?¶

Visualization:¶

In [82]:
# Extract the weekday from start_time
df_clean['weekday'] = df_clean['start_time'].dt.day_name()

# Calculate the average duration per weekday
avg_duration_per_weekday = df_clean.groupby('weekday')['duration_sec'].mean().reset_index()

# Ensure the weekdays are in the correct order
weekday_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
avg_duration_per_weekday['weekday'] = pd.Categorical(avg_duration_per_weekday['weekday'], categories=weekday_order, ordered=True)
avg_duration_per_weekday = avg_duration_per_weekday.sort_values('weekday')

# Plot the data
# create the first axes
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1, figsize=[14, 5]);

sns.stripplot(data = df_clean.query('duration_sec<duration_sec.quantile(0.99)'), x='weekday', y = 'duration_sec',
              color='b', size=1,jitter=0.35, ax=ax, alpha=0.2)

sns.scatterplot(data = avg_duration_per_weekday, x = 'weekday', y = 'duration_sec', s=100, color='red', ax=ax)
plt.title('Average Duration Of Bike Trips by Weekday:\nWith Average values (Red)'.title())
plt.xlabel('Weekday')
plt.ylabel('Average Duration (seconds)');

Observations¶

  1. Weekend vs. Weekday Durations:

    • The average duration of bike trips is notably higher on weekends (Saturday and Sunday) compared to weekdays. This suggests that people might be taking longer leisure trips during the weekends.

  2. Consistent Weekday Durations:

    • During weekdays (Monday to Friday), the average duration of bike trips is relatively consistent, ranging between 650 to 750 seconds. This indicates that weekday trips are shorter and possibly more routine or commuting-focused.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

  • Trip Duration and User Type: The box plot shows that subscribers generally have shorter trip durations compared to customers. This could indicate that subscribers use the service for shorter, more frequent trips, while customers might be using it for longer, occasional rides.

  • Bike Sharing and User Type: The clustered bar chart reveals that subscribers are more likely to share their bikes for the entire trip than customers. This behavior might be influenced by the frequency and nature of trips taken by subscribers.

  • Trip Duration and weekends: The average duration of bike trips is significantly higher on weekends (Saturday and Sunday) compared to weekdays. This suggests that people tend to take longer trips during the weekends, possibly for leisure activities.

  • Trip Duration and weekdays: During weekdays (Monday to Friday), the average duration of bike trips is relatively consistent, indicating that these trips are likely for commuting or other routine purposes.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

  • Member Gender and User Type: The distribution of member gender is consistent across both user types, with a higher number of male members. This suggests that gender does not significantly influence whether a person is a subscriber or a customer.
  • Trip Duration and Station Names: The scatter plots for start and end station names show a wide range of trip durations, indicating that certain stations may be associated with specific trip durations. However, due to the large number of unique station names, a more detailed analysis is required to draw specific conclusions.

These bivariate explorations provide valuable insights into the relationships between different features in the dataset, highlighting areas for further analysis and potential interventions to improve the bike-sharing service.

Conclusions¶

Summary of Main Findings:

  • Trip Durations: The distribution of trip durations is right-skewed, with most trips being relatively short and a few extending to very long durations. Using a logarithmic scale highlighted the long tail for extended trips.
  • User Types: Subscribers are the predominant user type and tend to have shorter trip durations compared to customers. They are also more likely to share their bikes for the entire trip.
  • Bike Sharing: The majority of trips do not involve sharing the bike for the entire duration, regardless of the user type.
  • Member Birth Years: Most members were born between 1960 and 1990, with some outliers in the birth year data indicating potential data entry issues or unusually old members.
  • Date Range: The dataset is limited to the months of February and March 2019.
  • Average Trip Duration: The average duration for all trips is about 500 seconds.
  • Day of the Week Trends: Most trips were taken on Thursdays and Tuesdays, while weekends have the least trip records.
  • Customer vs. Subscriber Behavior: Customers spend more duration on trips compared to subscribers. Additionally, customers travel for longer durations regardless of the day of the week, while subscribers have shorter trip durations.
  • Gender Trends: Females spend more duration on trips than males.
  • Weekend Trends: Trip durations on weekends are longer than on other weekdays.
  • Bike Sharing Policy: Only subscribers are allowed to share bikes on trips.
  • Trip Frequency by Weekday: Customer type does not significantly affect the number of trips per weekday.

Steps Taken:

  1. Data Cleaning: Handled missing values by removing rows with null values, corrected data types for consistency, and mapped categorical values to appropriate types.
  2. Exploratory Analysis: Conducted univariate and bivariate analysis to understand distributions and relationships between key features such as trip duration, user type, and bike sharing status.
  3. Visualizations: Utilized various plots (histograms, heatmaps, box plots) to explore and interpret data distributions and relationships, including temporal and geographic patterns.

These insights reveal key patterns in bike usage and user behaviors, which can inform strategies for improving the bike-sharing service and addressing user needs.
